I"<p>The premotor theory of attention argues that covert attention is actually a <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/spatial-attention-is-effector-agnostic-movement-intention-is-effector-specific">motor plan</a> being prepared. This action-oriented cognition is deeply compatible with <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/world-image-is-a-chicken-egg-problem">the enactive view in cognitive science</a>. The premotor theory of attention frames a high-level cognitive function in relation to a low-level motor coupling.</p>
